    summary:
      "The flood narrative is often reduced to a children's story — cute animals, rainbow, boat. But the actual text is devastating. It opens with God grieving. 'The LORD regretted that he had made human beings on the earth, and his heart was deeply troubled.' That's not the language of an angry judge; it's the language of a heartbroken parent. The violence of humanity has become so thorough that creation itself is corrupted, and God's response is to un-create — to return the world to the watery chaos of Genesis 1:2.\n\nNoah is 'righteous in his generation,' which is either a compliment or a qualifier, depending on how you read it. He builds the ark, loads the animals, and the waters come. The flood isn't just rain — the 'fountains of the great deep' burst open. The ordered separations of Genesis 1 (waters above, waters below) collapse. It's creation in reverse.\n\nBut then: God remembers Noah. The waters recede. The dove brings back an olive branch. And God makes a covenant — not just with Noah but with every living creature and the earth itself. The rainbow is a weapon hung up. In ancient Near Eastern imagery, the bow in the sky is a war bow, laid down. God is disarming.",
